why ethno-racial groups can be both perpetrators and victims of violence, why minority groups react differently to violence in comparable situations, and what the consequences are today for politics in both America and Europe.Violent America thus explores the effects of physical and discursive violence on the ways in which ethno-racial groups define themselves. Chebel d'Appollonia argues that the use of ethno-racial violence has been and remains an effective identity strategy by which all ethno-racial groups are able to integrate themselves into the mainstream of American society. She provides an alternative way of understanding the complex relationship between migrant phobia, multiethnic grievances, and inter-group conflicts in America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aEthnic conflict. 0aIdentity politicszUnited States. 0aViolencezUnited States. 4aCURRENT EVENTS. 4aDiscrimination & Race Relations. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / Legislative Branch.2bisacsh  aethno-racial violence, history of violence in America, ethno-racial conflicts inAmerica, dynamics of intergroup relations, racial prejudice, Inter-group violence, identity politics and violence.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075183340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150176758640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501767586423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501767586/original  a978-3-11-075183-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK